To fix the lofree block keyboard on XFCE (tested on devuan):

Open a text editor with root privileges to make the config file:
    sudo mousepad /etc/udev/hwdb.d/90-lofree.hwdb

Copy and paste the code block below into that file.
    # Remap Mac Media Keys to F-Keys for Lofree Block
    evdev:input:b*
     KEYBOARD_KEY_70040=f7
     KEYBOARD_KEY_70041=f8
     KEYBOARD_KEY_70042=f9
     KEYBOARD_KEY_70043=f10
     KEYBOARD_KEY_70044=f11
     KEYBOARD_KEY_70045=f12

Note: There must be exactly one space before each KEYBOARD_KEY line, or the kernel will not read the file correctly.

Also, you have to go to settings and unmap the media keys manually so XFCE doesn't override the hardware. Go to Start -> Keyboard. Click the Application Shortcuts tab, find any bindings using XF86AudioPlay, XF86AudioMute, XF86AudioLowerVolume, or XF86AudioRaiseVolume, and remove them by clicking on the row and clicking the Remove button at the bottom.

Apply the new map by running this:
    sudo udevadm hwdb --update
sudo udevadm trigger

Now to make it permanent. 
    This kernel-level fix is automatically permanent and doesn't require startup scripts. However, to clear out XFCE's background audio plugins from your current session and force the system to read the new F-keys properly, simply restart your computer.
